      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B02",
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "As accelerating voltage increases, more electrons reach the collector. Then the current falls sharply. Raise the voltage by another 4.9 volts and the pattern repeats.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "scan"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B02.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 10.09,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B02.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T15:01:39"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B03",
      "estimated_duration_s": 8,
      "narration_text": "Why can a mercury atom absorb about 4.9 electron volts in an inelastic collision, but not an arbitrary smaller amount?",
      "shot": {
        "type": "CARD",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "hold"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B03.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 8.19,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B03.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T15:01:39"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B04",
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "A classical internal oscillator could take a continuum of energies. Soft collisions would transfer small amounts, hard collisions larger amounts, and no single voltage spacing should dominate.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "compare"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B04.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 11.48,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B04.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T15:01:39"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B05",
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "Mercury instead has discrete internal energy levels. Its relevant first excitation lies roughly 4.9 electron volts above the ground state. There is no stationary level halfway between.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "levels"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B05.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 11.82,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B05.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T15:01:39"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B06",
      "estimated_duration_s": 5,
      "narration_text": "Below the gap, the excitation channel is closed.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "CARD",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "hold"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B06.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 3.35,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B06.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T15:01:39"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B07",
      "estimated_duration_s": 11,
      "narration_text": "An electron with less than the excitation energy can scatter elastically and keep nearly all its kinetic energy because the mercury atom is so much heavier. It cannot leave the atom in a nonexistent intermediate state.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "bounce"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B07.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 12.84,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B07.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T15:01:39"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B08",
      "estimated_duration_s": 11,
      "narration_text": "Once an electron has at least about 4.9 electron volts, an inelastic collision can lift the atom to the excited level. The electron loses that energy quantum and may no longer clear the collector's small retarding barrier.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "transfer"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B08.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 13.4,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B08.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T15:01:39"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B09",
      "estimated_duration_s": 9,
      "narration_text": "Increase the voltage further and electrons regain enough energy after one collision to reach the collector, so the current rises again.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "recover"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B09.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 7.83,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B09.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T15:01:39"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B10",
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "Near another 4.9-volt increment, two inelastic excitations become possible along the path. Electrons can again arrive depleted, producing the next current minimum.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "repeat"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B10.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 10.39,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B10.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T15:01:39"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B11",
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "The idealized curve therefore shows minima separated by the excitation voltage, about 4.9 volts. Contact potentials can shift the whole pattern, but not its characteristic spacing.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "measure"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B11.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 11.29,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B11.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T15:01:39"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B12",
      "estimated_duration_s": 8,
      "narration_text": "The repeating dips are an electrical ruler for a discrete atomic energy gap: the atom takes one allowed quantum, or stays in the lower state.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "CARD",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "hold"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B12.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 8.41,
